(3238, 5, '2010-04-02 12:35:19', '2010-04-02 10:35:19', '<em>4.2.10</em>\n\nGuest Blogger <a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/?s=Erin+Kim" target="_blank">Erin Kim</a>. Takes it away again...\n<p style="text-align: center"><a href="http://www.icp.org" target="_blank">Twilight Visions: Surrealism, Photography and Paris</a></p>\n<p style="text-align: center"><a href="http://www.icp.org" target="_blank">International Center of Photography</a></p>\n<p style="text-align: center">1133 Avenue of the Americas</p>\n<p style="text-align: center">New York NY 10036</p>\n<p style="text-align: center">Curated by Therese Lichtenstein</p>\n<p style="text-align: center"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center">I''ve been a bit nostalgic for my time in Paris, especially after seeing this particular exhibit at the International Center of Photography in New York. This is not your typical entry about fashion, style and beauty but the work I saw was too captivating to keep it from all the expat fans of I C U. And, imagine if elements of these brooding, surrealist photographs were incorporated into more fashion shoots; that could really produce some spectacular images!</p>\n<p style="text-align: center">Surrealists and their Paris of the late 1920s and 1930s.</p>\n<p style="text-align: center"><span style="text-decoration: underline"><strong>Brassai</strong></span></p>\n\n\n[caption id="attachment_3246" align="aligncenter" width="395" caption="Brassai: Nocturnal View from Notre Dame, 1933.  Estate of G. Brassa"]<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/brassainotredame.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3246   " src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/brassainotredame.jpg" alt="" width="395" height="457" /></a>[/caption]\n<p style="text-align: center"></p>\n\n\n[caption id="attachment_3276" align="aligncenter" width="374" caption="Brassa: Groupe Joyeux, Quatre Saisons , 1932  Estate of G. Brassa"]<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/balmusette.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3276 " src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/balmusette.jpg" alt="" width="374" height="495" /></a>[/caption]\n<p style="text-align: center"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center"><span style="text-decoration: underline"><strong>Ilse Bing</strong></span></p>\n<p style="text-align: center"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center"></p>\n\n\n[caption id="attachment_3250" align="aligncenter" width="382" caption="Eiffel Tower, Ilse Bing 1934  Estate of Ilse Bing/Edwynn Houk Gallery, New York. Courtesy Galerie Karsten Greve"]<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/ilsebing.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3250" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/ilsebing.jpg" alt="" width="382" height="480" /></a>[/caption]\n<p style="text-align: center">To the Surrealist artists and photographers of the 1920s and 1930s, Paris was the perfect stage set. Paris was rapidly modernizing, as electricity began to power most homes and businesses, and horse-drawn carriages were disappearing from its streets. Georges-Eugene Haussmann''s renovation of Paris was implemented in the 1860s, thus destroying much of the Old Paris", which was characterized by narrow, twisting streets lined by crumbling apartment houses and factory buildings. In the place of this Old Paris, wide boulevards with evenly lined trees and buildings were built, creating the Paris that we know today.The city was the perfect metaphor of a place that was nostalgic of its past, while wary of a future that would bring World War II. Surrealists were ever preoccupied with the nature and transcendence of Time.</p>\n<p style="text-align: center"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center"></p>\n\n\n[caption id="attachment_3267" align="aligncenter" width="393" caption="Ilse Bing: Danseusue-Cancan, Moulin Rouge, Paris, 1931. Zabriskie Gallery  Ilse Bing Estate/Courtesy Edwynn Houk Gallery, New York"]<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/Ilsebingdancer.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3267 " src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/Ilsebingdancer.jpg" alt="" width="393" height="506" /></a>[/caption]\n<p style="text-align: center"></p>\n\n\n[caption id="attachment_3279" align="aligncenter" width="576" caption="Ilse Bing: French Can Can Dancers, Moulin Rouge  Ilse Bing Estate/Courtesy Edwynn Houk Gallery, New York"]<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/ilsebingcancan.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3279 " src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/ilsebingcancan.jpg" alt="" width="576" height="430" /></a>[/caption]\n<p style="text-align: center"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center">With the lighting of Paris thanks to the advent of electricity, it also became a city of interchangeable light and obscurity. The light from the vaudeville theaters, the Eiffel tower, the street lamps would mix with the darkness in the narrow alleyways of Old Paris, the crumbling factory buildings and the brooding, ancient Gothic cathedrals. In the night, otherworldly, bizarre aspects of the city and its inhabitants would be revealed--rather than obscured--with this interplay of shadows and artificial light.</p>\n<p style="text-align: center"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center"></p>\n\n\n[caption id="attachment_3264" align="aligncenter" width="512" caption="Ilse Bing: Greta Garbo, 1932  Ilse Bing Estate/Courtesy Edwynn Houk Gallery, New York"]<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/gretagarbo.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3264 " src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/gretagarbo.jpg" alt="" width="512" height="383" /></a>[/caption]\n<p style="text-align: center"><span style="text-decoration: underline"><strong>Andr Kertsz</strong></span></p>\n<p style="text-align: center"></p>\n\n\n[caption id="attachment_3247" align="aligncenter" width="441" caption="Clock of the Acadmie Franaise, 1929 National Gallery of Art, Washington, Gift of The Howard Gilman Foundation and The Andr and Elizabeth Kertsz Foundation  The Estate of Andr Kertsz and the Jeu de Paume/French Ministry for Culture and Communication"]<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/kerteszclock.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3247  " src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/kerteszclock.jpg" alt="" width="441" height="572" /></a>[/caption]\n<p style="text-align: center"><span style="text-decoration: underline"><strong> </strong></span></p>\n<p style="text-align: center"><span style="text-decoration: underline"><strong>Eugne Atget: a proto-Surrealist</strong></span></p>\n<strong> </strong>\n<p style="text-align: center"><!-- 		@page { margin: 0.79in } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in } --></p>\n<p style="text-align: center"></p>\n\n\n[caption id="attachment_3260" align="aligncenter" width="466" caption="Eugne Atget The Wine Seller, 15 Rue Boyer 19101911 Gelatin-silver print (printed by Berenice Abbott) Gift of Walter P. Chrysler, Jr., Chrysler Museum of Art, Norfolk, VA."]<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/atget.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3260 " src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/atget.jpg" alt="" width="466" height="630" /></a>[/caption]\n<p style="text-align: center"></p>\n\n\n[caption id="attachment_3265" align="aligncenter" width="458" caption="Rue du Figuier Eugne Atget 1924 Gift of Walter P. Chrysler, Jr. by Exchange, Chrysler Museum of Art, Norfolk, VA."]<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/atgetrue.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3265 " src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/atgetrue.jpg" alt="" width="458" height="570" /></a>[/caption]\n<p style="text-align: center"></p>\n<p style="text-align: left"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center">These haunting images of Parisian nights are some of the most captivating portrayals of the most photographed city in the world.</p>\n<p style="text-align: center"></p>\nSee this exhibit at the <a href="http://www.icp.org" target="_blank">International Center of Photography</a> (New York, NY 10036) until May 9, 2010.\n<p style="text-align: center"></p>\n<p style="text-align: left"><!-- 		@page { margin: 0.79in } 		P { margin-bottom: 0.08in } --></p>', 'Nostalgic for a 1930s Paris', '4.2.10\n\nGuest Blogger Erin Kim. Takes it away again...\n\nI''ve been a bit nostalgic for my time in Paris, especially after seeing this particular exhibit at the International Center of Photography in New York. This is not your typical entry about fashion, style and beauty but the work I saw was too captivating to keep it from all the expat fans of I C U. And, imagine if elements of these brooding, surrealist photographs were incorporated into more fashion shoots; that could really produce some spectacular images!\n\nSurrealists and their Paris of the late 1920s and 1930s. (CLICK IMAGE AND/OR BLOG LINK TO VIEW POST)', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'nostalgic-for-a-1930s-paris', '', '', '2010-04-02 12:35:19', '2010-04-02 10:35:19', '', 0, 'https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/?p=3238', 0, 'post', '', 0);
