(3369, 5, '2010-04-28 07:51:03', '2010-04-28 05:51:03', '<em>4.28.10</em>\n\n<em><span style="color: #333399;">PATTERN ID: a culmination of cultures.</span> <span style="color: #888888;">Week #29. Post 1.</span></em>\n\nGuest Blog written and submitted by, <a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/?s=erin+Kim" target="_blank">Erin Kim</a>.\n\nClothing, textiles, decorative artsall have a story of their own. Each express a particular society''s customs and aesthetics, and each inform future generations of their history. From narratives told on West African textiles, the interlocking Cs of a Chanel purse to the floral patterns of an Indonesian batikall reveal specific cultural connotations. In contemporary context, many people are now exposed to an enormous, visual vocabulary thanks to globalization and the increased speed in the dispersion of ideas and images. This entire global narrative is now accessible to individuals who can then transform specific motifs and patterns to create new meanings and express new ideas.\n\n<a href="http://www.akronartmuseum.org/exhibitions/details.php?unid=1354" target="_blank">PATTERN ID</a>, an exhibit at <a href="http://www.akronartmuseum.org/" target="_blank">Akron Art Museum</a> in Akron, Ohio displays how 15 contemporary artists take advantage of this diverse visual language to express cultural identities that are also no longer defined or constricted within national borders and space. With so much movement between borders of religion, countries, ethnicity, class, ideologies, many individuals nowadays are influenced and characterized by a culmination of cultures rather than a single, restricting label.\n\nIndividuals are thus free to choose clothing, textiles and aesthetic motifs from all over the world to tell their own stories of who they are, and how they came to be:\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><a href="http://www.nmafa.si.edu/exhibits/shonibare/intro.html" target="_blank">Yinka Shonibare MBE</a>:</span>\nimages from National Museum of African Art\nA man of two cultures: born in Nigeria, currently living and working in London, England. Yinka Shonibare addresses the enduring impact of European colonialism on contemporary African identities, as well as the global web of economic and political interdependencies between Europe, Asia and Africa. He addresses these concerns through a variety of artistic mediums, and is informed by a variety of artistic influences: Rococo paintings of Jean-Honor Fragonard, decadent and colorful Dutch wax fabrics, motifs from West African textiles, the Russian ballet Swan Lake and literature of Oscar Wilde</p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n\n\n[caption id="attachment_3480" align="aligncenter" width="544" caption="Age of Enlightenment (c) Yinka Shonibare MBE"]<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/shonibare.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3480 " src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/shonibare.jpg" alt="" width="544" height="428" /></a>[/caption]\n\n[caption id="attachment_3446" align="aligncenter" width="500" caption="Three Graces (c) Yinka Shonibare MBE"]<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/threegraces-shonibare.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3446" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/threegraces-shonibare.jpg" alt="" width="500" height="416" /></a>[/caption]\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n\n\n[caption id="attachment_3448" align="aligncenter" width="517" caption="a still from Un Ballo in Maschera (A Masked Ball); 2004 (c) Yinka Shonibare MBE"]<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/amaskedball.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-3448   " src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/amaskedball-1024x684.jpg" alt="" width="517" height="345" /></a>[/caption]\n\n[caption id="attachment_3449" align="aligncenter" width="548" caption="a still from Un Ballo in Maschera (A Masked Ball); 2004 (c) Yinka Shonibare MBE"]<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/amaskedball2.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3449" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/amaskedball2.jpg" alt="" width="548" height="387" /></a>[/caption]\n\n[caption id="attachment_3501" align="aligncenter" width="542" caption="How to blow up two heads at once (c) Yinka Shonibare, MBE"]<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/shonibare2.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3501" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/shonibare2.jpg" alt="" width="542" height="455" /></a>[/caption]\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><a href="http://www.houkgallery.com/index-essaydi.html" target="_blank">Lalla Essaydi\nImages from Edwynn Houk Gallery</a></span></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;">Lalla Essaydi is a Moroccan artist who has also lived in Saudi Arabia for many years. She is now living and working in New York City. She takes Islamic calligraphy, a sacred art form practiced only by men, and applies them with painstaking detail to female bodies to create images that call attention to the highly complex realities of Arab women.</p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n\n\n[caption id="attachment_3453" align="aligncenter" width="602" caption="Les Femmes du Maroc, Grande Odalisque (c) Lalla Essaydi"]<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/grandeodalisque.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3453" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/grandeodalisque.jpg" alt="" width="602" height="480" /></a>[/caption]\n\n[caption id="attachment_3454" align="aligncenter" width="544" caption="Les Femmes du Maroc- Moorish Woman (c) Lalla Essaydi"]<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/femmesdumaroc-moorish.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3454" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/femmesdumaroc-moorish.jpg" alt="" width="544" height="693" /></a>[/caption]\n\n"In my art, I wish to present myself through multiple lenses -- as artist, as Moroccan, as Saudi, as traditionalist, as Liberal, as Muslim. In short, I invite the viewer to resist stereotypes. -Lalla Essaydi\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n\n\n[caption id="attachment_3466" align="aligncenter" width="545" caption="Harem Women Writing (c) Lalla Essaydi"]<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/lesfemmes.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3466 " src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/lesfemmes.jpg" alt="" width="545" height="432" /></a>[/caption]\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><a href="http://www.kehindewiley.com/" target="_blank">Kehinde Wiley</a>\nimages from <a href="http://www.npg.si.edu/exhibit/recognize/paintings.html" target="_blank">National Portrait Gallery</a></span></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;">Kehinde Wiley''s paintings of young African American athletes, musicians and regular men in the latest hip-hop fashion are larger than life. The authority and eminence of hip-hop, athletes and pop culture icons are established with motifs from Western European art from the 17th-19th centuries that are normally associated with European royalty and aristocracy.</p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n\n\n[caption id="attachment_3467" align="aligncenter" width="540" caption="Grandmaster Flash and the Furious Five (c) Kehinde Wiley"]<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/wiley1.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3467 " src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/wiley1.jpg" alt="" width="540" height="392" /></a>[/caption]\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n\n\n[caption id="attachment_3468" align="aligncenter" width="540" caption="Three Graces (c) Kehinde Wiley"]<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/wiley2.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3468 " src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/wiley2.jpg" alt="" width="540" height="402" /></a>[/caption]\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n\n\n[caption id="attachment_3469" align="aligncenter" width="540" caption="Triple Portrait of Charles I (c) Kehinde Wiley"]<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/wiley3.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3469 " src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/wiley3.jpg" alt="" width="540" height="317" /></a>[/caption]\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><a href="http://www.axisweb.org/seCVPG.aspx?ARTISTID=9891" target="_blank">Grace Ndiritu</a>\nImages from Axis Art</span></p>\n<p style="text-align: center; padding-left: 30px;">Images are taken from stills from her short "video paintings" called The Nightingale and Still Life: White Textiles. The artist gives sensuous performances in both videos. Largely inspired by Henri Matisse paintings, she celebrates movement and shape with the careful concealing and revealing of her body using West African fabric.</p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n\n\n[caption id="attachment_3472" align="aligncenter" width="540" caption="a still from The Nightingale (2003) (c) Grace Ndiritu"]<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/thenightingale.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3472 " src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/thenightingale.jpg" alt="" width="540" height="324" /></a>[/caption]\n\n[caption id="attachment_3474" align="aligncenter" width="500" caption="still from The Nightingale (2003) (c) Grace Ndiritu"]<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/nightingale.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3474" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/nightingale.jpg" alt="" width="500" height="400" /></a>[/caption]\n\n[caption id="attachment_3475" align="aligncenter" width="500" caption="a still from Still Life: White Textiles (2005-2007) (c) Grace Ndiritu"]<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/stilllife.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-3475" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/stilllife.jpg" alt="" width="500" height="400" /></a>[/caption]\n\nNot all of these works are on display at the Akron Art Museum. Around 40 works in Pattern ID include highly evocative and creative works from contemporary artists:\n<a href="http://www.sikkemajenkinsco.com/markbradford.html" target="_blank">Mark Bradford</a>, <a href="http://ionarozealbrown.com/" target="_blank">iona rozeal brown</a>, <a href="http://www.saic.edu/gallery/saic_profile_faculty.php?type=Faculty&amp;album=461" target="_blank">Nick Cave</a>, <a href="http://williecole.com/index.html" target="_blank">Willie Cole</a>, <a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcfour/documentaries/features/samuel-fosso.shtml" target="_blank">Samuel Fosso</a>, <a href="http://www.marxzav.com/artist.php?artistID=26#" target="_blank">James Gobel</a>, <a href="http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=113840238" target="_blank">Brian Jungen</a>, <a href="http://www.hauserwirth.com/artists/17/bharti-kher/biography/" target="_blank">Bharti Kher</a>, <a href="www.takashimurakami.com" target="_blank">Takashi Murakami</a>, <a href="http://mickalenethomas.com/" target="_blank">Mickalene Thomas</a> and <a href="http://www.ayauekawa.net/" target="_blank">Aya Uekawa</a>.', 'PATTERN ID: a culmination of cultures', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'pattern-id-a-culmination-of-cultures', '', '', '2010-04-28 07:51:03', '2010-04-28 05:51:03', '', 0, 'https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/?p=3369', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(3375, 4, '2010-04-24 13:18:40', '2010-04-24 11:18:40', '<em>4.20.10</em>\n\n<em><span style="color: #888888;">Diane Pernet.</span> <a href="http://www.dianepernet.typepad.com/" target="_blank">A Shaded View On Fashion</a> &amp; <strong>a film festival that may change your creative mind</strong>. Week #28. Post 5.</em>\n\nSeriously. If you live in Europe, you don''t want to miss this. But If you don''t no worries, this will not be the last post on Ms. Pernet''s endeavors.\n\nA Shaded View On Fashion is a blog I subscribe to and from whom I receive posts on a daily basis. This woman is fantastic. Odd and completely alternative, which is why she is creating and exhibiting people, places and things which are always intriguing.\n\nThe submission &amp; collaboration in Milan next with Vogue Milan. The submissions are from all over the world so if you are a film maker - submit!\n\nWatch the clip, these are the winners from last year...you''ll get the idea.\n<p style="text-align: center;"><object classid="clsid:d27cdb6e-ae6d-11cf-96b8-444553540000" width="480" height="270" codebase="http://download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=6,0,40,0"><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true" /><param name="allowScriptAccess" value="always" /><param name="src" value="http://www.dailymotion.com/swf/video/xar66m" /><param name="allowfullscreen" value="true" /><embed type="application/x-shockwave-flash" width="480" height="270" src="http://www.dailymotion.com/swf/video/xar66m" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true"></embed></object>\n<strong><a href="http://www.dailymotion.com/video/xar66m_asvoff-2009-winners-excerpts_creation">ASVOFF 2009 Winners Excerpts</a></strong>\n<em>envoy par <a href="http://www.dailymotion.com/AShadedView">AShadedView</a>. - <a href="http://www.dailymotion.com/fr/channel/creation">Dcouvrez plus de vidos cratives.</a></em>\n\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><em>To Learn more about how to submit and/or view click <a href="http://www.ashadedviewonfashionfilm.com/" target="_blank"><strong>HERE</strong></a></em></p>', 'A Fashion Film Festival Not To Be Missed. ', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'a-fashion-film-festival-not-to-be-missed', '', '', '2010-04-24 13:18:40', '2010-04-24 11:18:40', '', 0, 'https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/?p=3375', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(3376, 4, '2010-04-21 09:56:44', '2010-04-21 07:56:44', '<em>4.21.10</em>\n\n<em><a href="http://sophie-mhabille.com/index.php" target="_blank"><span style="color: #ff00ff;">Sophie Mhabille</span></a>  This is real Paris Fashion.</em><em> Week #28. Post 1.</em>\n\nWe are unveiling something new today, something I myself am very proud to announce and to have found.\n\nMademoiselle <a href="http://sophie-mhabille.com/index.php" target="_blank"><span style="color: #ff00ff;">Sophie Mhabille</span></a><span style="color: #ff00ff;">. </span>\n\n<span style="color: #ff00ff;"><span style="color: #000000;"><em>Petite bio cousu main, (mais pas trop coll mont...) - </em><span style="color: #ff00ff;"><em>Little Miss Organic, hand-sewn, (but not too stuck-up)</em></span></span></span>\n\nA young Parisian woman with not only killer style, beauty and confidence - but an eye for Paris street style that no <a href="http://facehunter.blogspot.com/" target="_blank">Face Hunter</a> or <a href="http://thesartorialist.blogspot.com/" target="_blank">Satorialist</a> can find. <em><strong>Yes, you can quote me on that.</strong></em> Sophie has lived in Paris all her life - works for Louis Vouitton and could quite possibly be one of the most stylishly smart people I have ever met. Read her bio <a href="http://sophie-mhabille.com/index.php/site/about/" target="_blank">here</a>.\n\nShe has just launched her own fashion blog - <a href="http://sophie-mhabille.com/index.php" target="_blank"><span style="color: #ff00ff;">www.sophie-mhabille.com</span></a> she figured, why not share the Paris eye candy with everyone else? And a PLUS - She writes in French and English - <span style="color: #800080;"><span style="color: #ff00ff;">English translation in fuschia, love it.</span> </span>\n\nAnd since Sophie is a friend and an absolute darling, she has agreed to be featured on I C U each week. New looks, Exclusive photos and insider Paris street style tid-bits.\n\nYes, its a collaboration.\n\nSo, <span style="color: #ff00ff;">Collaboration Numro 1.</span> <em>The Kenzo Dress &amp; Sophie. </em>\n\n<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/sophie-paris-fashion.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3377" title="sophie - paris fashion" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/sophie-paris-fashion.jpg" alt="" width="400" height="600" /></a>\n<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/sophie-mhabille-paris-fashion-4.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3379" title="sophie mhabille - paris fashion 4" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/sophie-mhabille-paris-fashion-4.jpg" alt="" width="400" height="600" /></a>\n\n<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/sophie-mhabille-paris-fashion-3.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3380" title="sophie mhabille paris fashion 3" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/sophie-mhabille-paris-fashion-3.jpg" alt="" width="400" height="267" /></a>\n\n<a style="text-decoration: none;" href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/sohie-mhabille-paris-fashion-2.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3381" title="sohie mhabille - paris fashion 2" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/sohie-mhabille-paris-fashion-2.jpg" alt="" width="400" height="267" /></a>\n\nRobe : <a href="http://www.kenzo.com/" target="_blank">Kenzo</a>, broche : Little Black (<a href="http://www.littleblack.ca/www.littleblack.fr">http://www.littleblack.ca/www.littleblack.fr</a> (sortie bientt)\n\n<span style="color: #ff00ff;">Dress: </span><a href="http://www.kenzo.com/" target="_blank"><span style="color: #ff00ff;">Kenzo</span></a><span style="color: #ff00ff;">, brooch: Little Black (</span><a href="http://www.littleblack.ca/www.littleblack.fr"><span style="color: #ff00ff;">http://www.littleblack.ca/www.littleblack.fr</span></a><span style="color: #ff00ff;"> (coming soon)</span>\n\nBrooch available here :<a href="http://www.etsy.com/shop/littleblack">http://www.etsy.com/shop/littleblack</a>\n\nTo view more of Sophie and Paris''s street style visit: <a href="http://sophie-mhabille.com/index.php" target="_blank"><span style="color: #ff00ff;">www.sophie-mhabille.com</span></a>', 'The Introduction of Mlle. Sophie Mhabille', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-introduction-of-mlle-sophie-mhabille', '', '', '2010-04-21 09:56:44', '2010-04-21 07:56:44', '', 0, 'https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/?p=3376', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(3395, 4, '2010-04-22 09:33:04', '2010-04-22 07:33:04', '<em>4.22.10</em>\n\n<em><span style="color: #291ba6;"><a href="http://www.ysl.com" target="_blank"><span style="color: #3366ff;">Y</span></a></span><span style="color: #291ba6;"><a href="http://www.ysl.com" target="_blank"><span style="color: #3366ff;">ves Saint Laurent</span></a></span><span style="color: #291ba6;">.</span><span style="color: #291ba6;"> </span>A legend &amp; a legend.</em><em> Week #28. Post 2.</em>\n\nToday I am delighted to introduce a guest blog from Ms. Rawlins. Fellow American turned Paris lover - traveler, restaurant connoisseur and overall fantastic lady.\n\nShe sneaked into Petit Palais with her trusty iphone and was able to capture a few images of this breath taking exhibit of a man and his legend...\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span><a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/ysl.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3396" title="ysl" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/ysl.jpg" alt="" width="595" height="326" /></a></span></p>\n\n<h2 style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: x-small;"><span style="font-weight: 800;"><span style="font-size: x-large;"><span><strong>\n</strong></span></span></span></span></h2>\n<p style="text-align: left;">From now until August 29,take a trip through therevolutionaryworks of the legend, <a href="http://www.ysl.com/" target="_blank"><span style="color: #3366ff;">Yves Saint Laurent </span></a>at the <a href="http://www.paris.org/Musees/PPalais/" target="_blank"><span style="color: #3366ff;">Petit </span></a><span><a href="http://www.paris.org/Musees/PPalais/" target="_blank"><span style="color: #3366ff;">Palais in Paris</span></a></span>. The exhibit boasts over300 looksbeginningwith his days at Dior in 1958 and ending with his last collection in 2002.</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;">It will take you on a journey through the iconic Safari collection of the 1960''s, to the luxurious Russian collection of the 1970''swith<span> it''s rich furs and gold detailing, then to his beloved Morocco andcontinuesinto the decadence of the 1980''s YSL complete with bows and of course shoulders <span style="color: #3366ff;">lines that defined the decade</span>, justto name a few of the highlights. </span></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span><a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/ysl-paris.jpg">\n</a></span></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span><a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/ysl-paris-2.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-3398" title="ysl paris 2" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/ysl-paris-2-768x1024.jpg" alt="" width="538" height="717" /></a></span></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span><a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/yves-st-laurent-paris-exhibit.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-3399" title="yves st laurent paris exhibit" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/yves-st-laurent-paris-exhibit-603x1024.jpg" alt="" width="422" height="717" /></a></span></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n<p style="text-align: left;"><span><span>The exhibit encores with a chrystal chandelier lit room,appropriately named"TheLastBall", that <span style="color: #3366ff;">displays the most famous evening lookspresented in a cascade down a red staircase.</span> And one must not forget his most famous </span><span>look</span><span>, "Le Smoking". An entire wall displays the evolution of"Le Smoking" from it''s creation in </span><span>1966</span><span> to its final reincarnation in 2002. </span></span></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span><span>\n<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/ysl-paris1.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-3401" title="ysl paris" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/ysl-paris1-614x1024.jpg" alt="" width="430" height="717" /></a>\n</span></span></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span><span><strong>Beautifully presented, the exhibitallows the viewer a glimpse into the life worksof the most celebrated designersof our time. </strong></span></span></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span><span><strong>\n</strong></span></span></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span><span><strong><a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/iconic-ysl.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3405" title="iconic ysl" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/iconic-ysl.jpg" alt="" width="413" height="487" /></a></strong></span></span></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span><span><strong><a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/ysl-paris-exhibit.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3406" title="ysl paris exhibit" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/ysl-paris-exhibit.jpg" alt="" width="385" height="493" /></a>\n</strong></span></span></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span><span><a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/yves-st.-laurent-paris.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3400" title="yves st. laurent paris" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/yves-st.-laurent-paris.jpg" alt="" width="595" height="351" /></a></span></span></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span><span><strong>Yves Saint Laurent: 40 Ans De Cration au Petit Palais</strong></span></span></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span><span><strong><strong>Muse du Petit Palais</strong></strong></span></span></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span><span><strong><strong>Avenue Winston Churchill</strong></strong></span></span></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span><span><strong><strong>75008 Paris</strong></strong></span></span></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span><span>Metro: Champs Elyses-Clemenceau, Concorde</span></span></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><span><span>Du Jeudi 11 Mars 2010 au Dimanche 29 Aout 2010.</span></span></p>', 'Isn&#039;t elegance forgetting what one is wearing? - YSL', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', '3395', '', '', '2010-04-22 09:33:04', '2010-04-22 07:33:04', '', 0, 'https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/?p=3395', 0, 'post', '', 0);
