(7564, 9, '2011-12-01 11:37:43', '2011-12-01 10:37:43', 'A true triple threat, <a href="http://aprilhubal.com/" target="_blank">April Hubal</a> is on her way to mastering photography, journalism and blogging, and lucky for us she is a longtime friend of the ICU family. After building her own magazine from the ground up and creating a <a href="http://aprilhubal.wordpress.com/" target="_blank">blog</a> with a dedicated following, it''s no wonder we couldn''t wait to pick her brain. Wouldn''t it be great if Paris is the next locale on her to-do list?\n\n-Christina Zervanos, Director of Media &amp; Press Relations, ICUinParis.com\n\n<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/photo.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-7583" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/photo.jpg" alt="" width="400" height="400" /></a>\n\n<strong>CZ: </strong>How did <em><a href="http://www.maniacmagazine.com/" target="_blank">Maniac Magazine</a></em> come to be?\n\n<strong>April: </strong><em><a href="http://www.maniacmagazine.com/" target="_blank">Maniac Magazine</a></em> came to be after 911, it was so hard to find a job in the creative field at that time. Originally I wanted to move to New York City, but that was out of the question, so the next best thing I thought would be to stay in Pittsburgh and create a magazine that caters to other young professionals. Pittsburgh predominantly caters to an older demographic so I thought it was time to change that persona. Without any money at all I sold enough advertising to fund the first issue, just by going from door to door.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>CZ: </strong>What do you want your readership to gain from <em><a href="http://www.maniacmagazine.com/" target="_blank">Maniac</a></em>?\n\n<strong>April: </strong>I want them to take away a piece of the Maniac lifestyle, whether it''s traveling like a maniac or shopping like a maniac. It''s living that high-low lifestyle: pairing a Chanel bag with an outfit from Target. That''s what we capture when doing a Maniac Jetset story-- we could be at a five star resort and then a motel. It''sall about having fun, not being stuffy, and doing what you love to do.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>CZ: </strong>You have your hands in a lot of creative outlets (photography, editorial styling, journalism, blogging); does one inspire you the most? And how do they interact and overlap?\n\n<strong>April: </strong>Yes, obviously photography is what drives my passion in life. <em><a href="http://www.maniacmagazine.com/" target="_blank">Maniac</a></em> allowed me to figure out the formula and nail it down so I can translate my passions into other areas. I actually just shot a celebrity cover and I wasn''t happy with the way the writer approached the story so I ended up writing it myself. In this particular case they overlapped perfectly.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>CZ: </strong>You have had the opportunity to shoot a few notable celebrities: share with us your favorites.\n\n<strong>April: </strong>They are all great in some way. I think AnnaLynne McCord, the <em>90210</em> star,was one of my favorites. She was so raw. I sat and spoke with her while she was getting her makeup done before the shoot and it really impacted the way I shot her and her personality really came out. She was speaking about the guy she was dating and how it wasn''t going well and how she was really pissed. To really get a glimpse of a celebrity''s real life can inspire something magical on set.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>CZ: </strong>Share with us a terror story from a shoot gone wrong.\n\n<strong>April: </strong>Oh goodness! There was just a really bad shoot in NYC and I don''t feel bad about saying what happened or who it was. It was Jennifer Esposito, who was married to Bradley Cooper for four months, and now I know why it only lasted that long. She pretty much had a break down on set, I''ve never experienced anything like that before. First she didn''t like her hair or makeup so she redid it herself. Then she didn''t like the clothes the stylist had pulled, gorgeous Lanvin dresses and Stella McCartney-- I mean who doesn''t like Stella McCartney? Then finally she said we weren''t representing her brand of food products correctly and brought in her own stylist while we had ours running around for more clothes. Finally she put on this dress that made her look like a hippie bag lady. It was just insane, we literally couldn''t finish the shoot. And it''s sad because she is a celebrity that represents a foundation for Celiac''s disease at the end of the dayshe cares more about her image than helping people and it just disgusted me.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>CZ: </strong>Who is the subject of your dream shoot? Paint the picture for us: location, dress, mood, theme, music...\n\n<strong>April: </strong>That''s so hard. Either one of the top ten models like a Kate Moss, or Keira Knightley. If it was Kate Moss I would probably pull something really minimalist for wardrobe and I''d let her personality dictate the shoot. Obviously I would love to shoot her in Paris! I would have the Rihanna album playing because that''s what I''m listening to right now.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>CZ: </strong>From Pittsburgh and still based there, you work heavily in New York and Los Angeles as well. Each city is uniquely different, particularly coast to coast; what do you gain from all of them? Do you identify with one the most?\n\n<strong>April: </strong>All of them are great! New York is a favorite just because you have so many like minded people in fashion that are able to contribute so the teams are fantastic there-- you have the best of the best in terms of styling, hair and makeup. LA is always nice because the weather is fantastic.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>CZ: </strong>Do you consider your success as a photographer to be parallel with your success as an editor/founder? Do you have greater hopes for one than the other?\n\n<strong>April: </strong>The magazine was started as a vehicle for my photography, so I''m happy to have a passion that is able to be paralleled with my success with the magazine. I never forget that when I''m creating, I''m very blessed.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>CZ: </strong>Is there a photographer or journalist you follow religiously-- someone who never ceases to inspire you??\n\n<strong>April: </strong>Mario Testino is a photographer who I admire a lot. And Terry Richardson. I don''t like him as a person but he has been doing a lot of creative things lately, he has a new book coming out with Lady Gaga he followed her around on her tour for some time. But the person who is most inspiring me right now is a director by the name of Melina Matsoukas. She is amazing. She is 29 and she has already shot and directed videos for Jennifer Lopez, Lady Gaga and Beyonce. Her video for Rihanna <em>We Found Love</em> is so visually stunning. I ask myself what Melina fantasizes about because to do videos this stunning she has to daydream all day. She inspires me because she is 29 and is spinning the entire music industry on one hand.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>CZ: </strong>Self taught and very successful, what advice would you give to aspiring photographers and/or business owners?\n\n<strong>April: </strong>For photographers, go to NYC and work under one of the a-list photographers assisting, them you will learn so much! In business, have a few mentors that you can call on daily if need be.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>CZ: </strong>What fashion magazine do you never miss an issue of?\n\n<strong>April: </strong>Nylon, Vogue and Elle are all my favorites.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>CZ: </strong>Is there one city whose style you are completely taken by? Why?\n\n<strong>April: </strong>NYC, because it is one of the riskiest, most free spirited and diverse cities, perfect to express individual style!\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>CZ: </strong>A fashionista yourself, how does this play into hiring the stylists you work with? What do you look for most in a stlyist?\n\n<strong>April: </strong>When choosing a stylist I look for someone that can pull a cohesive look throughout an entire spread, I don''t like a look that''s too feminine or too masculine. I love something that meets in the middle. I also do like mixing really expensive designers with local ones. When shooting a celebrity I look for a stylist who has worked with celebs prior, when doing fashion editorials I like someone who has a lot of experience in editorials, they really are completely different.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>CZ: </strong>What is your take on independent design?\n\n<strong>April: </strong>I love independent designers. They, in my opinion, have so much more to offer the public than a designer that is catering to the masses. It''s like they are giving you a part of their world not just designing what is being dictated to them\n\n<a href="http://www.aprilhubal.com/"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-7584" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/thumbnails.jpg" alt="" width="600" height="375" /></a>', 'ICU Exclusive Interview: April Hubal the Triple Threat', 'A true triple threat, April Hubal is on her way to mastering photography, journalism and blogging, and lucky for us she is a longtime friend of the ICU family.  After building her own magazine from the ground up and creating a blog with a dedicated following, it''s no wonder we couldn''t wait to pick her brain.  Wouldn''t it be great if Paris is the next locale on her to-do list?  ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'icu-exclusive-interview-april-hubal-the-triple-threat', '', '', '2011-12-01 11:37:43', '2011-12-01 10:37:43', '', 0, 'https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/?p=7564', 0, 'post', '', 0),
