(7864, 11, '2012-01-26 10:54:21', '2012-01-26 09:54:21', 'A chance encounter, <strong><em>ICU</em></strong> first met <strong><a href="http://www.francesco-marongiu.com/" target="_blank">Francesco Marongiu</a></strong> through <a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/2012/01/12/alessandra-montani-icu-exclusive-interview-with-the-international-model/" target="_blank">Alessandra Montani</a> in Paris when he was visiting from Milan. Talent in shoots for Francesco before, Alessandra raved about his style and aesthetic.\n\nImmediately drawn to Francesco, our brief meeting with him was nothing short of captivating and inspiring so we have kept in contact with the hopes of collaborating on a shoot in the near future!\n\nJust back from Berlin during the whirlwind of Fashion Week, Francesco found time to answer some of our questions... shedding light into the world of his mastered craft: photography.\n\n-Christina Zervanos, Director of Media &amp; Press Relations, ICUinParis.com\n<p style="text-align: left"><img class="size-full wp-image-7877" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/376062_10151019260935333_649525332_21977456_164734470_n.jpg" alt="" width="488" height="504" /></p>\n<p style="text-align: left">&nbsp;</p>\n<p style="text-align: left"><strong>CZ: <em>Did you study photography or are you self-taught?</em></strong></p>\n<p style="text-align: left"><strong>Francesco:</strong> I can answer both; I attended an academy of photography in Milan for two years, but my knowledge of photography, post-production, and styling are mostly a result of my personal studies. I research thousands of magazines, websites and blogs; photography has to be a continuous personal growth.</p>\n<strong>CZ: <em>How did you break into such a difficult industry?</em></strong>\n\n<strong>Francesco: </strong>I am just now starting to break in, but it has a very strong armor!Its not that easy to get work in this world; today, its based a lot on contacts and production of high quality works. I think that I am just at the beginning of my career and life as a fashion photographer. Its a really slow and long process that needs much patience and hard work.I remain patient and work hard in the best way that I can.\n\n<strong>CZ:<em>What is it like to be a photographer in the fashion capital of the world, Milan?</em></strong>\n\n<strong>Francesco: </strong>Its so stimulating because Milan has a really old fashion history. Here, you always find a lot of new ideas; you are able to meet people really linked with fashion which helps you grow a lot. At the same moment, it is so difficult because today''s fashion world is so expanded there is a lot of competition. Unfortunately, Italy has many problems as a country and theyre being reflected also in this field.\n\n<strong>CZ:<em>How does being located in Milan affect your photography and the talent you work with?</em></strong>\n\n<strong><em> </em>Francesco: </strong>To be honest, not as much as you would imagine. I really like traveling abroad, and prefer the taste and works of foreign countries -especially the Parisian one. I think that my photography is much more a mix of a lot of international tastes than a typical Italian print from Milan.\n\n<strong>CZ:<em> Multi-talented, your client list spans the beauty, fashion, and lifestyle spectrums shooting clients from Lindarico to Grey Goose; which do you prefer?</em></strong>\n\n<strong>Francesco: </strong>I absolutely prefer the fashion world. A lot of times working with clients like Grey Goose or Maserati I have to shoot still life or just report to a project mid-progress. I prefer much more to work with models, and in the fashion world because there I can interact with and move my subjects, create a picture from the beginning; I don''t just take pictures, I make them.\n\n<strong>CZ:<em>How would you describe your aesthetic?</em></strong><img class="size-full wp-image-7879 alignright" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/francesco2.jpg" alt="" width="360" height="427" />\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Francesco: </strong>I prefer to use natural light. I really like playing with colors and post-production; Im obsessed with perfection, so sometimes I spend hours or days to work on every picture until its totally perfect. A picture in front of me on the monitor is like a white canvas in front of a painter.\n\n<strong>CZ:<em>Who would you say your greatest influence has been in developing your aesthetic?</em></strong>\n\n<strong>Francesco: </strong>Im influenced by a lot of other artist and people that I follow and Ive met during my life. My favorites are Paolo Roversi, Mert &amp; Marcus, James Meakin and Steve McCurry.\n\n<strong>CZ:<em>When shooting your talent, do you make an effort to personally connect with them or keep it very professional and distant? Why?</em></strong>\n\n<strong>Francesco: </strong>Personally, I am a really open person and really love to connect and interact with people, especially with new ones. Everyone has something to give and teach to you and opens to you a new little world and knowledge. I think that connections a lot of times makes works stronger, more emotional and let everyone in the set enjoy more the shooting.\n\n<strong>CZ:<em>During a shoot, what is your playlist?</em></strong>\n\n<strong>Francesco: </strong>Usually it depends on the models'' and client''s tastes; I usually ask them their favorite music, so that I can create the best mood and energy to work. I also have made my own playlist with powerful and funny music for set moments... the top are: Pupkulies &amp; Rebecca, the Xx, Caribou, Ratatat, Dirty Doering, Fritz &amp; Paul Kalkbrenner, the Gossip, Hercules and Love Affair, Jesper Ryom...\n\n<strong>CZ:<em>Tell us about your favorite shoot: theme, location, vibe, talent, styling</em></strong>\n\n<strong>Francesco: </strong>One of my best shootings ever was absolutely the campaign for <em>Lindarico </em>last year. We shot during the summer in Milan, and it was the situation where everything went perfectly: everyone and everything was linked like in a perfect web. We had really great outfits to shoot; the clients were the most kind and gentle ever; weather and light were perfect for all two shooting days; we choose really great shooting locations around Milan, and I was shooting one of my favorites models, Szilvia.\n\n<strong>CZ:<em>Tell us about your dream shoot - every little detail!</em></strong>\n\n<strong><em> </em>Francesco: </strong>Uh, this is maybe the most difficult question!!You have to know that I dont come from Milan, but from a mountain area between Venice and Austria. For this reason, I really love and am very attached to animals, nature and awesome landscapes. So, maybe my dream shoot would be a campaign for some high label with all these things connected.\n\nIm undecided between a shooting in the winter, on a frozen lake with all the white mountains surrounding while the model is wearing a white fur; shes walking with some wolves in the lake''s reflection.\n\nAnother is during the summer in India with the model wearing a long and vibrant haute couture dress while shes riding a Rajan  a very rare elephant able to swim that you can find only in few Indian islands  and theyre swimming in a crystal water with white reflecting sand under.\n\ndo you think it could be enough?\n\n<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/francesco1.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-7878 aligncenter" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/francesco1.jpg" alt="" width="600" height="895" /></a>\n<div><strong>An<a title="http://ICUINPARIS.COM/" href="http://icuinparis.com/" target="_blank">ICUINPARIS.COM</a> Interview Production.</strong></div>\n<strong> </strong>\n\n<strong> </strong>\n\n<strong> </strong>\n<div><strong><a title="http://ICUINPARIS.COM/" href="http://icuinparis.com/" target="_blank">ICUINPARIS.COM</a> 2011 All Rights Reserved.</strong></div>\n<strong> </strong>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong> </strong>\n\n&nbsp;', 'ICU Gets Charmed by Milan-based Photographer, Francesco Marongiu', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'icu-gets-charmed-by-milan-based-photographer-francesco-marongiu', '', '', '2012-01-26 10:54:21', '2012-01-26 09:54:21', '', 0, 'https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/?p=7864', 0, 'post', '', 0),
