(8017, 11, '2012-02-21 13:03:51', '2012-02-21 12:03:51', '<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/02-383_.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-8028 alignright" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/02-383_.jpg" alt="" width="560" height="374" /></a></p>\n<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/02-383_.jpg"> </a><em>"The first time I ever saw Robin Foster play was two years ago in Brittany, France. They set up an outdoor stage in the middle of a field, with cliffs falling to the ocean just a stroll away and a sky that lived in eternities of stars.</em>\n\n<em>Since then, I''ll confess, I''m hooked. </em><a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/02-383_.jpg"> </a>\n\n<em>As a true fan (yeah, you could say a little ''die-hard''), I can personally and honestly say Robin Foster''s music is not only remarkable, it touches you. It is the kind of sound that gives you those funny brain tingles accompanied by goose bumps that run up your arm when the climax of the song begins to build.</em>\n\n<em>His recent success and growth comes as no surprise, neither does his reaction to it all. A character of all sorts, Robin has always kept a humble tone through humor and his love for impersonations (his ability to copy accents is a bit too good). His latest album, <strong><a title="robin foster" href="http://www.robinfoster.fr/" target="_blank">Where Do We Go From Here?</a> </strong>Featuring <strong><a title="dave pen" href="http://iamdavepen.wordpress.com/" target="_blank">Dave Pen</a></strong> of the group <a title="archive" href="http://archiveofficial.com/" target="_blank">Archive</a> and <strong><a title="ndidi o" href="http://ndidio.net/" target="_blank">Ndidi O</a></strong>. is just the start to what is to come, so it was only natural that ICU''s public relations guru, Christina Zervanos, sat down with Robin to conduct this exclusive interview of the brain behind the music. </em>\n\n<em>Enjoy and enjoy. I''ll leave it now to Christina (and a little snippet from the new album never hurts to set the mood :)"</em>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><object width="560" height="315"><param name="movie" value="https://www.youtube.com/v/XAdikN6NrWk?version=3&amp;hl=en_US" /><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true" /><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always" /><embed type="application/x-shockwave-flash" width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/v/XAdikN6NrWk?version=3&amp;hl=en_US" allowfullscreen="true" allowscriptaccess="always"></embed></object></p>\n<em> - Christan Summers,<span style="color: #888888;">Owner/Founder ICUINPARIS.COM </span></em>\n\n<em><span style="color: #888888;"> </span></em>\n\n<address> </address> <address><span style="color: #888888;"><!--more-->\n</span></address><strong> </strong><strong>CZ: What inspires your music?</strong>\n\nRF: Essentially emotions and things that bring them out, could be a film and the ambiance it''s giving, often lights and moods in scenes. Certain directors really bring it out of me, Michael Mann, James Grey, David Lynch and of course the wonderful Sean Ellis-- they all share a certain approach in their lighting that seems to inspire me.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>CZ: You consistently reference film in your composed tracks; what is your personal favorite film soundtrack?</strong>\n\nRF: <em>For a Few Dollars More</em>-- All of Morricone''s work is spellbinding but this is one of my earliest memories of being moved by music, still does it today.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>CZ: Which film score composer would you like to collaborate with? Why?</strong>\n\nRF: Morricone, of course.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>CZ: A band member of <em>Beth</em> for seven years prior to your solo career, you continue to collaborate. What do you gain from these different mediums of composition?</strong>\n\nRF: Ironically I wasn''t very open minded to collaborating when I was in a group, but am much more now that I''m a solo artist! It''s great to work with people who don''t do the same thing you do, I rarely sing, scares me to death, so I''m in awe of certain singers and their talents, if it''s the right combination you can really bounce off each other. As a result the sum becomes greater than the equal parts.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>CZ: Is there a quality you are drawn to when determining artists with whom you wish to collaborate? For example, on this last album, you work with <a href="http://ndidio.net/" target="_blank">Ndidi O</a>. and <a href="http://iamdavepen.wordpress.com/" target="_blank">Dave Pen</a> who embody such different music styles; is there a common thread?</strong>\n\n[caption id="attachment_8019" align="alignright" width="500" caption="Left to right: Ndidi O., Robin Foster, Dave Pen. / Photo: Christian Geisselmann"]<img class="size-full wp-image-8019  " src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/01-022_.jpg" alt="" width="500" height="333" />[/caption]\n\n&nbsp;\n\nRF: <a href="http://iamdavepen.wordpress.com/" target="_blank">Dave</a> and <a href="http://ndidio.net/" target="_blank">Ndidi</a> are much more similar that you''d think, the three of us in the same room is always a nice recipe for trouble, but the good kind of trouble... I think we all have these split personalities as artists, a dark side and a light side that fit together, so on stage the darkness comes out and it''s really intense for us, then once we''re off stage and unleashed in the general public we tend to go a bit mental.\n\n- <a title="nididi o, robin foster " href="http://youtu.be/ZgtT3HRdyW8" target="_blank">Click here</a> to listen to the Ndidi O. Collaboration\n\n- <a title="dave pen, robin foster " href="http://youtu.be/uoguTV3cH_A" target="_blank">Click here</a> to watch the latest music video featuring Dave Pen\n\n<strong>CZ: You have reaped tremendous success via providing soundtracks for popular US shows such as <em>One Tree Hill </em>and <em>Criminal Minds</em> and campaign music for global brands like Hugo Boss and Kenneth Cole; do you consider these to be your greatest career triumphs to date?</strong>\n\nRF: They are all great opportunities, the <a title="hugo boss" href="http://youtu.be/JSOkJstMEkA" target="_blank">Hugo Boss advertisement</a> is a great triumph, obviously it helped me get where I am now but the real triumph with that is that the song in question <em><a title="blue nights at dusk, robin foster" href="http://youtu.be/ioDrvYEdHVY" target="_blank">Blue Lights At Dusk</a></em> was the result of a battle with the record producer, him saying the song was "a mess, doesn''t make sense", he didn''t believe in that track at all, whereas for me it was the track that summed me up the most, so that song being on the album and then used for Hugo Boss was a huge triumph! <a title="kenneth cole, robin foster " href="http://youtu.be/ti5O0BEki1s" target="_blank">Kenneth Cole</a> is an ongoing collaboration, they come up with these great ads that are more like little films often based on a slogan or a question, very cool.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>CZ: To you, what is the recipe of a brilliant album?</strong>\n\nRF: As a listener, it''s got to take hold of you by the guts and heartstrings and then keep you there ''til its last note, then you want to go back for more. As an artist it''s got to be sincere, if you can put yourself completely into the music, blood, sweat and tears-- the works-- then I believe people will respond to it.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>CZ: A composer, songwriter, and multi-instrumentalist you pour yourself into many creative outlets; does one inspire you most, or are they the necessary elements of a true artist?</strong>\n\nRF: I just look at it all as music and emotions, I don''t separate, soundtracks, albums, singles, videos, adverts, whatever-- it''s all just about expressing music and emotions, the song decides.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong><a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/01-226-Custom-Name.jpg"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-8031" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/01-226-Custom-Name.jpg" alt="" width="480" height="320" /></a>CZ: Share with us your most memorable performance.\n</strong>RF: There''s been a few, the last is going to be hard to beat, we played at the <em>Trans Musicales</em> in Rennes, France, last December it was just one of those magical moments when everything and everyone just comes together on stage and you get a huge rush up the back of your neck from start to finish... I even attempted a would be guitar solo at some point, naughty.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>CZ: Have you written one song or lyric that you feel represents who you are?</strong>\n\nRF: Like I said before, it''s got to be <em>Blue Lights At Dusk, </em>the proof in self belief and sticking to your guns.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>CA: What inspires your solo album titles <em>Life is Elsewhere </em>and<em> Where Do We Go From Here?</em></strong>\n\nRF: <em>Life is Elsewhere</em> was the result of a conversation I had with my girlfriend, we were really sick of where we were at the time, the way certain people were around us, it was just a reminder to ourselves that the world is a bigger place and you have to look for it. It''s also the title of a great book by Kundera. <em>Where Do We Go From Here?</em> is more complex and has several meanings, it follows on from <em>Life is Elsewhere </em>very well for a start, but it predominantly deals with life and death. There was a lot of that going on when I was recording, it was a hard time and I was looking for a way forward, I suppose music is one constant journey towards... something.\n\nFor all tour dates and to read, see and hear more of Robin Foster visit his website here :http://www.robinfoster.fr\n\n<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/big-collage-robin-foster.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-8032 aligncenter" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/big-collage-robin-foster.jpg" alt="" width="915" height="458" /></a>\n<p style="text-align: center;">All photos: <a title="Christian Geisselmann" href="http://www.ChristianGeisselmann.com" target="_blank">Christian Geisselmann</a></p>\n\n<div style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/?s=interview&amp;submit.x=0&amp;submit.y=0" target="_blank">Click <strong>here </strong>to read more exclusive ICU interviews.</a></div>\n<div style="text-align: center;"><strong>An<a title="http://ICUINPARIS.COM/" href="http://icuinparis.com/" target="_blank">ICUINPARIS.COM</a> Interview Production.</strong></div>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong> </strong></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong> </strong></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong> </strong></p>\n\n<div style="text-align: center;"><strong><a title="http://ICUINPARIS.COM/" href="http://icuinparis.com/" target="_blank">ICUINPARIS.COM</a> 2011 All Rights Reserved.</strong></div>\n&nbsp;', 'ICU&#039;s Exclusive Interview with Robin Foster', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'icus-exclusive-interview-with-robin-foster', '', '', '2012-02-21 13:03:51', '2012-02-21 12:03:51', '', 0, 'https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/?p=8017', 0, 'post', '', 0),
