(8740, 4, '2013-01-12 20:10:20', '2013-01-12 19:10:20', '<p style="text-align: left;">Last week was the reception for Jeff Muhs''s <em>The Origin of Nymphs</em> at Lyons Wier Gallery in Chelsea. Muhs is a classically trained artist and while visiting the Louvre in Paris, he began to contemplate the enduring image and its profundity throughout time. He studied <em>La Grande Odalisque,</em>her structure and expression in particularand it''s relation to our present day society.This led him to a deeper study of images such as<em> Napoleon I on his Imperial Throne (after Ingres)</em>and<em>Venus and Cupid (after Pellegrini).</em></p>\n<p style="text-align: left;">His pieces are meant to be blurry, a unique method to use when bringing to life such historical figures. The relation of our time, compared to the time it was originally created bares a hard fact and question that the artist may have asked himself as well; do we actually <em>see</em> things anymore? Do we see and take the time to appreciate beauty the way it used to be?</p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/IMG_2741.jpg"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-8742" title="Lyons Gallery Jeff Muhs" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/IMG_2741-1024x768.jpg" alt="" width="612" height="458" /></a></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/IMG_2742.jpg"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-8743" title="Lyons Gallery Jeff Muhs" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/IMG_2742-1024x768.jpg" alt="" width="604" height="453" /></a></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/IMG_2743.jpg"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-8744" title="Lyons Gallery Jeff Muhs" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/IMG_2743-1024x768.jpg" alt="" width="604" height="453" /></a></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/IMG_2740.jpg"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-8741" title="Lyons Gallery Jeff Muhs" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/IMG_2740-1024x768.jpg" alt="" width="604" height="453" /></a></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;">JEFF MUHS<em>The Origin of Nymphs</em></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;">January 5th - February 9th, 2013</p>\n<p style="text-align: center;">Lyons Wier Gallery</p>\n<p style="text-align: center;">542 West 24th St. NY NY 10011</p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a title="lyons wier gallery" href="http://www.lyonswiergallery.com" target="_blank">www.lyonswiergallery.com</a></p>', 'JEFF MUHS The Origin of Nymphs', 'Last week was the reception for Jeff Muhs''s The Origin of Nymphs at Lyons Wier Gallery in Chelsea. Muhs is a classically trained artist and while visiting the Louvre in Paris, he began to contemplate the enduring image and its profundity throughout time. He studied La Grande Odalisque, her structure and expression in particular and it''s relation....\n', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'jeff-muhs-the-origin-of-nymphs', '', '', '2013-01-12 20:10:20', '2013-01-12 19:10:20', '', 0, 'https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/?p=8740', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(8749, 4, '2013-01-15 22:40:42', '2013-01-15 21:40:42', '<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/IMG_2775.jpg"><img class="wp-image-8755 alignright" title="picasso-black-white-guggenheim" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/IMG_2775-768x1024.jpg" alt="" width="386" height="515" /></a>\n\nPicasso Black and White is on exhibit at the Guggenheim Museum NYC this month.\n\nI did not expect to be so captivated. Picasso of course is captivating, I mean, how else are you a master painter who was also one of the most infamous lovers next to Casablanca?\n\nRight.\n\nGuggenheim divided the space by time period and/or commission which more often than not, was in parallel with Picasso''s love affairs.\n\nThe artist was reported to state that color "weakens," which is why it has been left behind here - in a vast spiral of black and white Picasso''s desire to highlight his works'' unique structure and anatomy is presented.\n\nWe strolled upwards through time starting in the early 1900''s, ending eloquently with a <em>The Kiss</em> of 1969.\n\nA beautiful ode to a magnificent artist. The exhibition will run through January 23rd 2013.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-8750" title="picasso-black-white-guggenheim-horse" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/picasso-black-white-guggenheim-horse.jpeg" alt="" width="650" height="459" />\n\n<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/picasso-black-and-white-at-the-guggenheim-new-york-2.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-8754" title="picasso-black-and-white-at-the-guggenheim-new-york-" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/picasso-black-and-white-at-the-guggenheim-new-york-2.jpg" alt="" width="650" height="439" /></a>\n\n<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-8753" title="picasso-black-white-guggenheim-rape-sabines" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/picasso-black-white-guggenheim-rape-sabines.jpg" alt="" width="443" height="560" />\n\n<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-8752" title="picasso-black-white-guggenheim-kitchen" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/picasso-black-white-guggenheim-kitchen.jpg" alt="" width="560" height="390" />\n\n<a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/picasso-black-white-guggenheim-kiss.jpeg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-8751" title="picasso-black-white-guggenheim-kiss" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/picasso-black-white-guggenheim-kiss.jpeg" alt="" width="650" height="483" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><a title="Guggenheim Museum NYC " href="http://www.guggenheim.org/new-york" target="_blank">Guggenheim Museum</a></strong></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1071 5th Ave. and 86th Street</strong></p>', 'Picasso Black and White at the Guggenheim NYC', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'picasso-black-and-white-at-the-guggenheim-nyc', '', '', '2013-01-15 22:40:42', '2013-01-15 21:40:42', '', 0, 'https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/?p=8749', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(8768, 4, '2013-01-17 06:17:34', '2013-01-17 05:17:34', '<p style="text-align: center;">There are some things that you cannot explain why you like them but you know you do. You know that this thing, this perfect composition of things has struck a perfect chord in you - all you want to do is bottle it up and stash it away.</p>\n<p style="text-align: center;">This is how I feel about the content of<strong>The Big Book Of Chic</strong>.</p>\n<p style="text-align: center;">Of course Miles Redd has an extraordinary eye - lobsters on the roof? I mean, that is exceptional. However it is the book''s entirety that brings a full-on creative tsunami; from the photography to the lay-out, page design and infamous quotes placed strategically through-out.</p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a title="Paul Costello" href="http://www.paulcostello.net/html/index.html" target="_blank"><strong>Paul Costello</strong></a> is the photographer, published by no other than <a title="Assouline" href="http://www.assouline.com/" target="_blank">ASSOULINE</a>.</p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Big-Book-of-Chic-Flat-Cover-LR.jpg"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-8772" title="Big Book of Chic Flat Cover mile redd" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Big-Book-of-Chic-Flat-Cover-LR-736x1024.jpg" alt="" width="530" height="737" /></a></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/IMG_2761.jpg"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-8775" title="Big Book of Chic miles redd" src="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/IMG_2761-768x1024.jpg" alt="" width="544" height="725" /></a></p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.icuinparis.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/tumblr_md91rpAUZH1rn1ljyo1_500.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-8774" title="tumblr_md91rpAUZH1rn1ljyo1_500" src="https://www.icuinparis.com